Daniel Cassidy (1943 Brooklyn – October 11, 2008) was a controversial American writer. He was also a filmmaker, musician, and academic.
<ref name="SFGateObit">cite news|last1=Doyle |first1=Jim |title=Irish American Daniel Cassidy dead at 65 |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Irish-American-Daniel-Cassidy-dead-at-65-3189914.php |accessdate=7 April 2016 |work=SFGate.com |publisher=San Francisco Chronicle, Hearst Communications Inc. |date=15 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703094630/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2008%2F10%2F15%2FBAK813H4B0.DTL |archive-date=July 3, 2009 |dead-url=no |df= </ref>

Life
Cassidy was the son of a navy chief petty officer. He graduated from New York Military Academy on a full scholarship and attended Cornell University but never graduated.<ref>cite web| url=https://cassidyslangscam.wordpress.com/2015/03/23/an-unqualified-failure/| website=cassidyslangscam| title=An Unqualified Failure
| accessdate=2015-03-30</ref>

Cassidy worked for the ''New York Times'' as a news assistant. He was a professional musician, starting as a reed player, and cutting an album as a singer and composer. He played Carnegie Hall, the Pasadena Conference Center|Civic Auditorium, and The Tonight Show – performing with comedian George Carlin,<ref>cite web |url=http://www.irishartscenter.org/music_archive.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-10-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120903212359/http://www.irishartscenter.org/music_archive.html |archivedate=September 3, 2012 |df=mdy-all </ref> Kenny Rankin, and Lilly Tomlin.

Cassidy married Clare McIntyre, in 1983. In 1995, he founded and co-directed the Irish Studies program at New College of California.<ref name="SFGateObit" />

His work appeared in ''The San Francisco Chronicle'',<ref>cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/1998/07/29/ED83401.DTL | title=Churches of Fire in Ireland and the South | first=Daniel | last=Cassidy | date=July 29, 1998 | work=The San Francisco Chronicle</ref> the ''New York Observer'' and the ''Atlantic Monthly''.

Cassidy died of pancreatic cancer at his home in San Francisco.<ref name="SFGateObit" />

